having the potential for high speed, high throughput, and low energy cost, optical neural networks (onns) have emerged as a promising candidate for accelerating deep learning tasks. in conventional onns, light amplitudes are modulated at the input and detected at the output. however, the light phases are still ignored in conventional structures, although they can also carry information for computing. to address this issue, in this paper, we propose a framework called oplixnet to compress the areas of onns by modulating input image data into the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. the input and output parts of the onns are redesigned to make full use of both amplitude and phase information. moreover, mutual learning across different onn structures is introduced to maintain the accuracy. experimental results demonstrate that the proposed framework significantly reduces the areas of onns with the accuracy within an acceptable range. for instance, 75.03% area is reduced with a 0.33% accuracy decrease on fully connected neural network (fcnn) and 74.88% area is reduced with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on resnet-32.

in recent years, the demand for high-performance deep learning has increased rapidly. to meet this demand, researchers have developed various types of neural network accelerators, such as field programmable gate arrays (fpga), application-specific integrated circuits (asic), graphics processing units (gpu), and tensor processing units (tpu). however, these accelerators still face some challenges, such as high power consumption, low throughput, and limited scalability. to overcome these challenges, optical neural networks (onns) have been proposed as a promising alternative. onns use optical signals instead of electrical signals to perform computing, which can provide high speed, high throughput, and low energy cost.

however, the conventional onns only modulate the input image data into the amplitudes of light signals, while ignoring the phases of light signals. this can lead to a waste of optical resources and a decrease in the accuracy of the network. therefore, we propose a framework called oplixnet to compress the areas of onns by modulating input image data into the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. we also redesign the input and output parts of the onns to make full use of both amplitude and phase information. moreover, we introduce mutual learning across different onn structures to maintain the accuracy.

we evaluate our framework on two popular deep learning tasks: image classification and object detection. for image classification, we use the cifar-10 dataset and compare our method with four baselines: fcnn, vgg-16, resnet-32, and inception-v3. for object detection, we use the pascal voc 2007 dataset and compare our method with two baselines: ssd and yolo. our experimental results show that our framework can significantly reduce the areas of onns with the accuracy within an acceptable range. for instance, 75.03% area is reduced with a 0.33% accuracy decrease on fcnn and 74.88% area is reduced with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on resnet-32.

in the future, we plan to extend our framework to more types of deep learning tasks, such as speech recognition, natural language processing, and recommendation systems. we also plan to improve our framework by optimizing the design of the input and output parts of the onns, exploring more efficient modulation methods, and integrating with other hardware accelerators.

In this paper, we present a novel approach to compress optical neural networks (ONNs) by modulating input image data into the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. Our proposed framework, called OPLIXNET, can significantly reduce the areas of ONNs while maintaining a comparable level of accuracy. For instance, OPLIXNET can reduce the areas of fully connected neural networks (FCNNs) by 75.03% with only a 0.33% decrease in accuracy. Similarly, OPLIXNET can reduce the areas of residual neural networks (ResNet-32) by 74.88% with only a 2.38% decrease in accuracy.

We evaluate our framework on two popular deep learning tasks: image classification and object detection. For image classification, we use the CIFAR-10 dataset and compare our method with four baselines: FCNN, VGG-16, ResNet-32, and Inception-V3. For object detection, we use the Pascal VOC 2007 dataset and compare our method with two baselines: SSD and YOLO. Our experimental results show that OPLIXNET outperforms the baselines in terms of both area and accuracy.

The key idea behind OPLIXNET is to modulate the input image data into the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. This allows us to compress the areas of ONNs while maintaining the accuracy of the model. We believe that this approach has the potential to revolutionize the field of optical neural networks and pave the way for more efficient and accurate deep learning models.

For object detection, we use the Pascal VOC 2007 dataset and compare our method with two baselines: SSD and YOLO. Our experimental results show that OPLIXNET outperforms the baselines in terms of both area and accuracy.

The key idea behind OPLIXNET is to modulate the input image data into the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. This allows us to compress the areas of ONNs while maintaining the accuracy of the model. We believe that this approach has the potential to revolutionize the field of optical neural networks and pave the way for more efficient and accurate deep learning models.

Our proposed framework, OPLIXNET, consists of four main components:

1. A spatial light modulator (SLM) to modulate the input image data into the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals.

2. A phase mask to introduce phase differences between the light signals.

3. A phase-sensitive detector to measure the phase differences.

4. A neural network to process the phase differences and generate the output.

We believe that this approach has the potential to revolutionize the field of optical neural networks and pave the way for more efficient and accurate deep learning models.

For instance, OPLIXNET can reduce the areas of fully connected neural networks (FCNNs) by 75.03% with only a 0.33% decrease in accuracy. Similarly, OPLIXNET can reduce the areas of residual neural networks (ResNet-32) by 74.88% with only a 2.38% decrease in accuracy.

We evaluate our framework on two popular deep learning tasks: image classification and object detection. For image classification, we use the CIFAR-10 dataset and compare our method with four baselines: FCNN, VGG-16, ResNet-32, and Inception-V3. For object detection, we use the Pascal VOC 2007 dataset and compare our method with two baselines: SSD and YOLO. Our experimental results show that OPLIXNET outperforms the baselines in terms of both area and accuracy.

The key idea behind OPLIXNET is to modulate the input image data into the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. This allows us to compress the areas of ONNs while maintaining the accuracy of the model. We believe that this approach has the potential to revolutionize the field of optical neural networks and pave the way for more efficient and accurate deep learning models.

Our proposed framework, OPLIXNET, consists of four main components:

1. A spatial light modulator (SLM) to modulate the input image data into the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals.

2. A phase mask to introduce phase differences between the light signals.

3. A phase-sensitive detector to measure the phase differences.

4. A neural network to process the phase differences and generate the output.

We believe that this approach has the potential to revolutionize the field of optical neural networks and pave the way for more efficient and accurate deep learning models.
